description:
From 6 years in isolation to sounding the alarm, Buddhist Gelong Thubten reveals the hidden epidemic no one is talking about with stress, depression, buddhism, meditation, mental health and more.

Thubten is one of the UKs most influential meditation teachers, who spent 6 years in isolated meditation retreats, including one which lasted 4 years. He is also the bestselling author of books such as, Handbook for Hard Times: A Monk's Guide to Fearless Living.

He explains:
緒 The hidden mental health crisis thats silently destroying your emotional well-being.
緒 Why Western culture increases anxiety, depression, and disconnection
緒 The biggest myths about meditation and how to meditate properly.
緒 The real reason your meditation practice isnt working.
緒 How screen time and phone addiction are hijacking your brain and inner peace.
緒 Why rejecting pleasure can lead to lasting connection and clarity.
緒 How unresolved trauma controls your mind and how mindfulness can free you.

comments.text: Hey Steve! I love your accent. I am a huge fan of your content. I have been thinking about how much simpler life could be for me if I joined a monastery. I have even been taunted at my places of employment. Meditation has helped me through this. I place myself in a mindset that if I lose everything I will still be okay. I appreciate those that have given up everything to pray for world peace. I am slowly purging things myself. Anxiety has almost halted me completely at times. I have a deep desire to help others and I have much of my life. With this stalking I have to focus on myself. I thoroughly enjoyed this content. I do miss the sense of community I came from when I lived in Atlanta Georgia. I think of going back often as well. For my happiness and peace I am willing to let everything go now. comments.text:
A bit personal for me since I have been trying meditation for a little over a year now and have slowly felt more discouraged, but this episode really hit the mark.

This shined a light on the fact my meditation practice was likely failing due to two major problems. 1) I was anticipating the high in the sense I was expecting instant relief from the internal stress. 2) I was going into it with too much of a competitive spirit that my next meditation had to be better than the first rather than letting nurture take its course.

Thank you for all of you that made this episode possible.

comments.text:
@DAndrea.John.88don't give up on meditation!!

I also stumbled a bit in the beginning, mostly from having the wrong idea of what I should have been doing/expecting. I wish somebody told me at the start that there are MANY types of meditation from all over the world, each a different technique with a different purpose.


Buddhist meditation is called vipassana meditation (the word vipassana is Sanskrit and means "to see things as they really are")

I highly recommend the videos from Michael Kewley (search his name in YouTube) this is where I discovered how to do it properly and along with Michaels teachings (he was also a monk for 40+ years) the difference it's made to my life is immeasurable.

I hope it helps
comments.author: @Soulace100

comments.text:
@philipweece1756I highly recommend the videos from Michael Kewley (search his name on YouTube) if this video resonated with you. I hope it helps
